'The sea is ours': Surrounded Bolivia hopes court will reopen away to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a masonry-covered naval quarters in La Paz.
Public buildings fly a sea-blue flag.
Naval bases from Titicaca Lake to the Amazon are marked with the slogan: "The sea is ours to the right.
It's a duty to get it back."
Across surrounding Bolivia, the memory of the coastline they lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still fresh – like the need to navigate the Pacific again.
That hope is probably the highest it has been in decades, while Bolivia is awaiting a ruling by the International Court of Justice on October 1, after 5 years of talks.
"Bolivia has the momentum, the spirit of unity and peace, and naturally expects the outcome with a positive attitude," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the IGH ruling on big screens across the country, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will find in favor of Bolivia’s claim that – after decades of sporadic negotiations – Chile is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia a sovereign passage to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president – who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year – also has many that depend on Monday’s verdict.
"We are close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will decide in Bolivia’s favor – and that few will change if they do.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to allocate Chilean territory, and has suggested that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the IRH's verdict comes just six months after the final verdict, shows that the case "was not complicated," says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And rather than helping Bolivia’s cause, the past four years may have slowed it down.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
Morales’ aggressive rhetoric hampered any remaining Chilean benevolence, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to conduct subsequent talks.
The two countries exchanged last ambassadors in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was extraordinarily quick.
On Monday, Bolivia will "bring an extraordinary opportunity to begin a new era of relations with Chile" and an opportunity to "end 139 years of differences with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific," he said.
"The verdict is an opportunity to see what we need to overcome the past."
