John Edward: Language Skills Essential for World Citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a slew of achievements of academic excellence, and it continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, only enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other community businesses.
With more than 30,000 schools across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their position as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a customized school curriculum, we see that world languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to someone in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It's a powerful reminder that we can't just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of scholars who studied foreign languages achieved a higher grade A.
The data, collected from SCIS's 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students achieved a higher grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 of those who studied French, and 63 of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages now, as a subject choice, have the same prestige as the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission on Occupations and Skills found in 2014 that of the reasons employees provide why they struggle to fill jobs, 17 percent are attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person above the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That's why it's so important now to invest in today's children's language education.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered essential for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to achieve success, regardless of what the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment, that languages are still extremely important for the country's future, and therefore they must be reflected in education.
Truly, modern languages should truly be regarded as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
I'm fine with the fair.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools.
