North Korea says it will "decisively" disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions exacerbated its distrust of the United States and that the country would certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons without such qualities.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant measures of goodwill" in the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, breaking down the nuclear test site, and promising not to increase nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We don't see a consistent response from the U.S.," he said.
"Without any confidence in the U.S., there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances, we will certainly not unilaterally disarm first."
While Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to nuclear weapons removal under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took gradual steps, his words seemed meaningful in that it did not unconditionally reject unilateral removal of nuclear weapons as Pjongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between a U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore when Kim undertook to work for the "destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula" while Trump provided guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for tight international sanctions against North Korea.
"The U.S. urges the 'destruction of nuclear weapons first' and exerts more pressure by tightening the level of sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way, and even objecting to the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is a dream of people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions are aggravating our distrust."
Ri did not say anything about plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump on which the U.S. leader drew attention at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings over the past five months between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in, adding: "If the party in this issue of nuclear destruction were South Korea and not the US, the destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end."
The tone of Ri's speech was nevertheless dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea's rockets would be directed at the U.S.'s landmass after "Mr. Bose President" Trump called Kim a "fire-fighter" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea last year, praised Kim abundantly for his courage for taking steps to disarm, but he said that much work still needs to be done and that sanctions must remain there until North Korea destroys nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn't have a timeframe for this, saying "it doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps they have taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the United Nations Security Council on Thursday that "the application of sanctions by the Security Council must continue with diligence and without ceasing until we realize the full, final, confirmed destruction of nuclear weapons."
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea in an effort to drain funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the outskirts of the UN General Assembly and afterwards said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip there hasn't gone well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, but North Korea accused him only hours later of making "gang-like demands."
North Korea, in a meeting with Moon, promised to demolish a missile site and also take a nuclear complex if the United States "consistent measures."
He said Kim told him that the "corresponding measures" he wants to see are security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore as well as steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on enough russian
A new course at Harvard University this year allows all of its undergraduate students to get more sleep in an effort to counteract the growing macho culture of studying by caffeine-driven "all-night sessions."
An academic has found that students at the world's top university are often uninformed when it comes to the basics of how to look after themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at the Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes to be the first of its kind in the U.S.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had told her how important sleep is - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was presented for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how they improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at the Harvard Medical Faculty and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to enter the course after it was found that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The hour-long course involves a few interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory, where students need to click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep time routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know what the health impact of choosing to smoke cigarettes is," Prof Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in "studying all night" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
To make sure you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's "secret weapon" should be to avoid stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even to avoid it to gain weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, making you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to pursue a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with each other.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and being aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and lead you to struggle to get on the sheep.
