National Trust Listens to Bats' Secret Life
New research is being conducted on a estate in the Scottish Highlands that aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common and soprano dwarf bats as well as the brown longhorn and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand indicators.
Expert clan channels of all surveys will check the frequency of bat calls and determine which species do.
A habitat map and report will then be compiled to create a detailed landscape-scale view of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as pasture creation and how to best manage forest lands for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping place and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as well as fly paper and some chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting activities, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-orientation technique to show off bugs and obstacles on their flight greetings.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, is very serious about bats.
It has ten trained experts who regularly do surveys and sleepover inspections and sometimes perform rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threave estates in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate manager David Thompson said the estate was the ideal site for them.
"Here at Threave we have a wonderful area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of veteran trees and all the good habitat.
But there's so much about bats that's still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us better understand what they need to thrive."
He stresses the need to search for bats before maintenance is done in properties because it is possible that the unknowing destruction of a single birthplace could mean the death of up to 400 females and young ones and could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb or prevent them or destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, urged the public to jump in to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species, we don't know how their populations are doing."
